Title:     Apple, IBM, others start superhighway.
             (Apple joins computer vendors and telecommunications firms
             in Cross Industry Working Team) (Brief Article)
Author:    Streeter, April


-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Washington - Apple has banded together with more than two dozen computer
vendors eager to start work on the data superhighway.

Last month Apple, AT&T Co., BellSouth Corp., IBM Corp. and others,
announced formation of the Cross Industry Working Team, or XIWT, a group
dedicated to accelerating the deployment of the electronic information
network.

Promoted by the Clinton administration and industry luminaries, including
former Apple CEO John Sculley, the data highway has been characterized as
a high-speed, high-bandwidth national network able to deliver digital
video and audio to millions of users.

XIWT, a membership organization with a $20,000 entrance fee, plans to
develop by this spring a white paper outlining ways to implement the
basic infrastructure required for the network, as well as recommendations
for pilot programs.

The new data highway will reportedly allow connections to the Internet,
the current international data network, but will operate at higher speeds
and implement stiffer security measures than those now in place.
