Title:     Data highway hamburger.
             (information superhighway) (Levitations)
Author:    Levitan, Arlan


Abstract:  The information superhighway is mismanaged by the government.
           Internet is about to be opened to commercial use when the
           National Science Foundation's ban is lifted, and users will be
           overwhelmed by junk electronic mail (E-mail) and other
           electronic solicitations. In 1993, commercial accounts make up
           more than half of new Internet users. The Federal
           Communications Commission continues to sell parts of the
           frequency spectrum to private enterprise, leaving a paucity of
           bandwidth for free public amateur radio so that vacuous memos
           can be transmitted quickly. The objective of VP Al Gore's
           information infrastructure agenda is to foster private
           investment so that the infrastructure can be built, which
           allows for such detrimental monopolies as the Bell
           Atlantic/Tele-Communications International (TCI) merger.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Info Superhighway? Go Play in the Road

Hang onto your keyboards, folks. The year 1994 is going to be a bumpy
ride for anyone who was gullible enough to swallow the "Information at
Your Fingertips" gruel that's been spoon-fed to us for the last 12
months. There are more than enough wonderful surprises waiting in the
wings to cause one to suspect that George Orwell wasn't wrong--just off
by a decade.

The freewheeling Internet, which has evolved into the information channel
of choice for computing cognoscenti over the last 20 years, will undergo
a wrenching change this year, as the National Science Foundation's ban on
commercial use of the net is lifted.

If you think that flame wars of the past have been a waste of bandwidth,
just wait until junk E-mail and other electronic solicitations start
spreading faster than a brushfire through Laurel Canyon. Thousands of
businesses have made preparations to pounce on the buying power of
millions lining up for Internet access. For the last year, over half of
the new users jumping on the net have been so-called "commercial"
accounts.

Computer-hip staffers in the Clinton Administration established an
Internet address for correspondence shortly after taking office. The
connection is currently just one-way; don't expect an answer to your
electronic missive, but be assured that Big Brother has been watching the
net for awhile. Just ask the fellow in California whose angry and
admittedly tasteless comments about George Bush in one of Internet's
political forums last year prompted a visit from a pair of FBI agents the
next day.

Trust Us, We're The Government

The American people supposedly own the airwaves, but that hasn't kept the
Federal Communications Commission from selling off more of the frequency
spectrum to private enterprise every year. As a result, the small amount
of bandwidth that is currently allocated to amateur radio--the only venue
where communication of packetized data remains both public and free--is
being cut away more methodically than the Pacific Northwest's old-growth
forest. Of course, that's a small price to pay to allow millions of
wireless PIM owners to FAX mindless memos to each other.

In case you missed it, Al Gore and his buds released their long-overdue
term paper last September, entitled "The National Information
Infrastructure: Agenda for Action" and co-sponsored by Big Al and
Commerce Secretary Ron Brown (the original $6 million man). Critics were
quick to point out that the proposal had less meat on its bones than a
Frank Perdue reject.

According to the white paper, the government's primary role in building
our so-called information superhighway should be limited to fostering
private investment in building the requisite network infrastructure. If
"fostering private investment" means standing by and staring at the
ceiling while Bell Atlantic and TCI merge to create the world's largest
corporate conglomerate, I don't feel like hanging around for the dividend
check.

Instead of thousands of independent info-service suppliers, I suspect
we'll end up with the information equivalent of retail superstores:
close, convenient, canned data that's pasteurized, homogenized, and
predigested so there's no need to activate your neural paths. I don't
know about you, but I'm looking forward to the digital equivalent of HBO,
The Weather Channel, and Home Shopping Network about as eagerly as I
would a series of rabies shots.

"Don't worry," coos Washington. "We'll make sure that there's reasonably
priced, universal information access for everyone." Who's kidding who?
For five bucks a month tacked onto the average phone bill, poor kids will
get access to millions of pages of textual information that might help
them pull themselves up by their bootstraps--if their school cared enough
to teach them to read.

Only the well-heeled will be able to afford the slick, interactive,
MTV-format education that comes down the wire. That's just what we need:
a generation of nuclear physicists who matriculated from Beavis and
Butthead U.

Since the cosmos will be at our fingertips, there'll be no need to
venture forth into the real world. And since perception is reality, who
cares what's really going on outside? We'll be riveted to our comfy
computer recliners, watching cool interactive full-motion videos on the
grandeur of nature, while someone quietly strip-mines the Grand Canyon.

As our government spends time issuing vague policy statements, the
opportunity to build a nationwide information network that truly belongs
to the American people is fading faster than Ross Perot's run for the
White House.

The techno-politicians are like deer frozen to the asphalt, staring in
mindless fascination while fiber-optic headlights relentlessly bear down
on them. Road pizza, anyone?
