Title:     Market reality turns visions to nightmares.
             (effects of marketplace on fruition of industry visions for
             future) (Channel Watch)
Author:    Humphrey, Charles


Abstract:  The new technological and distribution visions in the computer
           industry have suffered setbacks in 1993. The vision of a data
           superhighway held by the Clinton administration has turned out
           to be naive and ridiculous. Apple's former CEO John Sculley
           held to his vision of the Newton personal digital assistant
           and neglected its mainstay, the Macintosh, which now suffers
           from the strength of Microsoft Windows and the low prices of
           microcomputers. IBM's Louis Gerstner stated that his
           struggling company did not need vision. Intelligent
           Electronics' Richard Sanford devised the business model of the
           office-product superstore, but his vision has faltered under
           profit pressures. Visions must take the imperatives of the
           marketplace into consideration, and the successful ones are
           those that execute the business plan.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Last Year, PC Visionaries Got a Cold Dose of the Real World

That "vision thing," arguably the linchpin of the entire computer
industry, limped out of 1993 battered and bloodied. From Washington (the
capital of the nation) to Washington (the center of the PC universe) to
California, technological and distribution ideas were hammered by the
harsh realities of the marketplace.

For example, candidates Bill Clinton and Al Gore campaigned partially on
a vision of a data superhighway that would be all things to all people.
It was a naive, blank-page view of the world that crashed smack-dab into
the installed base of networks.

John Sculley, late of Apple, clung to his vision and pushed Newton out
the door. Unfortunately, the company's cash cow, Macintosh, was being
buzz-sawed by the twin blades of Windows and cutthroat pricing in the PC
world, which sliced off the Mac's technological advantage, and left it
bloated and overpriced.

Of course, one of the most damaging blows to vision was dealt when IBM's
chief executive, Louis Gerstner, frustrated by constant questions about
his view of the future, commented that vision was the last thing the
struggling giant needed.

Nor was vision spared the wrath of reality on the distribution front.
Richard Sanford, chief executive of Intelligent Electronics, the Exton,
Pa.-based franchiser/aggregator, had hoped to build a national chain of
office-product superstores featuring a product mix designed around the
core of future office technology--PC products--rather than consumables.

Success shattered that vision. True, BizMart drove PC products'
contribution to total sales up to 40 percent. Unfortunately, in a
business with storewide gross-margin requirements in the low- to
mid-20-percent range, the business model of the office-product superstore
failed to support the profit pressures of the PC industry. BizMart was
sold to Office Max, where strategists spent much of the year ruthlessly
paring PC sales back to roughly 12 percent of revenues.

I Had a Vision

Does all this mean that market visionaries should ignore their
inspirations, writing them off as the effect of overindulging in chili?
Absolutely not. But the environment within which visions must be applied
has changed dramatically.

Consider perhaps the single most fundamental shift in the channel last
year--which, ironically enough, can ultimately be traced back to Richard
Sanford's views of the world. It was he who pioneered cost-plus
franchising. Under this scheme, franchise fees based on a total,
bundled-value package gave way to a cost structure under which resellers'
payments were based on points over product costs. Additional charges for
value-added services were levied on a use-only basis.

This radical approach to the market, eventually embraced by all
franchisers, paved the way for the aggregator business, which was
essentially a distribution model. And when it first appeared nearly six
years ago, I, too, had a vision. But mine was based less on insight than
on simple business metrics.

Aggregation places franchisers in direct competition with distributors.
Distribution is an efficiency business, and no one distributes as
efficiently as distributors. Aggregators would thrive only as long as the
leading hardware vendors placed artificial authorization requirements on
the channel. When those barriers were toppled, and distributors were
approved to sell top-name systems, aggregators would fall.

At the same time, I conjured up a scenario in which a leading distributor
would amass its own network of captive customers, imagining that as the
most cost-effective way to move product from point A to B. Both those
"visions" took shape late last fall when Merisel signed an agreement to
buy the franchise business of ComputerLand for a cool $110 million.

Vision Tempered By Market

All this suggests that there's still a place in a fast-maturing market
for vision. But those visions must be applied to the imperatives of the
marketplace, and the visionaries that succeed will not be those with the
longest horizon, but rather those who execute the business plan.

Which brings us back to Apple. John Sculley paid for his commitment to
his vision by losing his job. Apple's business model demanded that
management focus on fixing the competitive erosion damaging the
Macintosh, rather than introducing a new computing paradigm.

Nevertheless, Sculley's dream has merit. With all its initial warts,
Newton remains a successful introduction. By October, Apple was reporting
that 50,000 units had been sold. Newton was simply a less-than-perfect
implementation of a vision that undoubtedly will be corrected. After all,
how many revisions did it take before Windows ultimately conquered and
changed the market?

PC industry visions are not all predestined to serve as the butt of
"Doonesbury" comic strips, as did Newton. Not, at least, when they are
applied to real-world applications and successfully implemented.
