Title:     Zenith's PC-to-cable link brings data highway home.
             (Zenith Datasystems' Homeworks PCTV-R modem) (Brief Article)
Author:    Vaughan-Nichols, Steven J.


-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Another access ramp recently added to the coming "data superhighway" is
Zenith's Homeworks PCTV-R. This new modem/network scheme en-ables you to
transmit and receive data over standard coaxial TV cable.

Cable wiring's biggest allure is raw speed. A single data channel can
fire data at up to 0.5 megabits per second (Mbps), and the effective
throughput is closer to 2 Mbps, thanks to multiplexing. That's a lot
faster than ordinary modems, which plod along by comparison at 0.192
Mbps.

The robust speed and bandwidth of products like Homeworks will help turn
multimedia wide-area networking into a reality, say market analysts. PC
systems linked to cable TV via Homeworks-type modems may be the future of
community data/video networks.

Homeworks can send or receive files, data, and programs without
interrupting one moment of "The Simpsons." A standard cable splitter
funnels broadcast signals to your TV, data to your PC. You'll need the
Homeworks modem, of course, and the network will require a Homeworks
central unit, or hub, to manage traffic.

The device's potential already has attracted developers such as Spry,
with its Windows-based AIR Navigator for Internet access. Working in
tandem with Homeworks, AIR Navigator can tap the Internet's E-mail
system, newsgroups, and file-hunting programs at speeds previously
reached only by dedicated Internet sites.

Among several cable companies reportedly interested in Homeworks is the
giant Tele-Communications Inc., which is currently testing the product in
Utah.
