Title:     Fit to print: choosing a personal or color printer.
             (includes related articles on workgroup printers, ecological
             aspects, consumer advice, resolution and color inkjets)
Author:    Stone, M. David


Abstract:  The first step towards buying a printer is determining which
           technology is best for the kind of work that is done. The two
           most common choices are personal black-and-white printers for
           desktop microcomputers and inexpensive color printers.
           Dot-matrix printers are noisy and produce low print quality,
           but inkjet printers use a kind of dot-matrix technology that
           eliminates those problems, although inkjet-printed documents
           are prone to smudging. Laser printers use specks of toner
           rather than drops of ink, so there is no problem with
           smudging. Resolution is an important consideration when
           shopping for printers. The standard for business laser
           printing is now 600-by-600 dpi, while inkjets are just
           beginning to achieve 600-by-300 dpi. Inkjets have the unique
           ability to offer black-and-white printing as well as
           high-quality color at an affordable price. Paper, ports, fonts
           and memory influence the buyer's choice as well.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

This is supposed to be the age of the electronic superhighway, but your
business still runs on paper, and your printer is your most important PC
peripheral. More than with any other kind of computer hardware, buying a
printer is an exercise in making choices: With most other equipment, the
main factor is how much money you have to spend, with more cash buying
more performance or capacity. With printers, you face fundamentally
different options--your printing needs can throw your price
considerations out the window.

If you want to print on multipart forms, for example, you'll have to get
an impact dot matrix printer, and put up with the mediocre output quality
and racketing noise that even the best and quietest matrix printer makes
compared to other technologies. At the other end of the spectrum, if you
want the finest photo-realistic color output, you may need a
dye-sublimation printer--which means high initial cost, reliance on
specially coated stock instead of standard copier paper, and buying a
second printer for black-and-white work.

In short, although the usual issues of price and performance (meaning
speed and print quality) are important, your first priority in choosing a
printer is to determine which technology best fits your needs.

In this Shopper's Guide, we'll look at the two liveliest parts of the
printer market--personal black-and-white printers for desktop PCs and
affordable color printers. The latter range from personal printers to
networkable publishing and presentation resources for office use. (See
the sidebar "One Printer, Many Users" for a look at heavy-duty,
network-oriented black-and-white office lasers.) We'll follow the same
pattern you'll use in making decisions--concentrating first on issues
that'll help you pick a technology, and then on particular printer
features.

Dot Matrix: Don't Bother

Dot matrix, once the workhorse printer and the sole choice for graphics
output, is fading into history as laser and inkjet prices continue to
fall. If you doubt it, look at the latest low-priced printer from dot
matrix king Epson--the Stylus 300, an inkjet with a street price around
$200.

The sad truth is that even today's much-improved dot matrix printers are
noisy, and their print quality is no match for inkjet printers. Their
only advantage is their ability to print multipart forms, where you need
an impact to make an impression through multiple copies.

If that's what you need, you're stuck with dot matrix technology; the
best advice is to get the best bargain you can among 24-pin matrix models
with the narrow- (8.5x11-inch) or wide-carriage (11x17-inch) paper
handling you need. Nonetheless, because impact matrix printers occupy
such a narrow niche these days, we'll ignore them from now on.

Technically, inkjets and lasers could be called dot matrix printers,
too--they form letters and graphics from a matrix of tiny dots, printed
one line at a time with inkjets and one page at a time with lasers. But
since they produce finer dots, and in most cases more dots per inch than
impact matrix printers, inkjets and lasers produce more fully formed text
characters and more finely detailed graphics.

Putting Dots On Paper

Inkjet printers form dots by spraying drops of ink from small nozzles.
Most inkjets use heating elements to vaporize the ink, forming a bubble
of expanding gas (think of the bubbles in boiling water) that forces a
drop out of the nozzle. Epson's Stylus 800 uses a different, piezo-based
technology, using vibrations to contract an element, creating pressure
that ejects ink drops.

How the printer forms and aims ink drops is only part of the
print-quality factor. Use a porous paper, for instance, and drops will
tend to bloom as they soak into the paper, leading to a slightly fuzzy
appearance. In fact, inkjet drops tend to bloom a bit in any
case--despite comparable resolution, even the best liquid ink naturally
yields less crisp results than laser printers' toner.

Water-soluble liquid ink also introduces a smudge factor. On early
inkjets like Hewlett-Packard's original DeskJet, you could actually
see--and, naturally, smear--the wet ink if you printed a graphic with
solid black areas. HP and other manufacturers have worked hard to
formulate quick-drying, less smudging inks, but you can still smudge an
inkjet page if you rub it with a damp finger or handle it immediately
after printing (especially in humid weather). One possible exception to
this rule, not yet available for testing at this writing, is Lexmark's
new IBM ExecJet II. Lexmark claims the ExecJet's ink uses a dye that's
water-soluble in an alkaline environment, but not in the acidic
environment typical of most paper stock.

Laser printers are smudge-free because their dots consist of specks of
toner instead of drops of ink. Lasers--as they're collectively called,
though some use LED or LCD instead of laser technology--are
electrophotographic printers. That means that a light source is used to
electrostatically charge a rotating drum with an image of the page. The
drum picks up toner particles and transfers them to paper, where heat
fuses them to the paper.

Big Dots, Little Dots: Resolution

When it comes to output quality, the type of dots isn't as important as
their size, measured in terms of dots per inch (dpi). Other things being
equal, higher resolution means crisper edges for text and graphics, fewer
"jaggies" in diagonal lines, and more shades of gray for better-looking
images, with fewer dithering patterns (combinations of adjacent dots that
fool the eye into seeing gray shades).

Formerly, the standard resolution for laser printing was 300x300 dpi--and
300 or 360 dpi is the value most inkjet printers tout when advertising
"laser quality." When HP introduced its LaserJet 4, the standard for
business laser printing shifted to 600x600 dpi (a level not widely
matched by inkjets, although a few, such as HP's DeskJet 1200C, offer
600x300 dpi).

The change is largely due to a new generation of laser printer engines,
which provide higher resolution at a slightly lower price than the
previous crop of 300-dpi en-gines. Along with these new 600-dpi units,
however, has come a new batch of still less expensive 300-dpi lasers,
with street prices dipping close to $500.

Do you really need 600-dpi resolution? If most of your printing is plain
text, with most of that in the 10- and 12-point font sizes of business
correspondence, odds are you won't see any difference between 300- and
600-dpi output unless you look very closely. On the other hand, if you
use small or large type--below 8 points or above 20 points, say--the
difference in quality becomes obvious, with characters appearing crisper,
cleaner, and better formed.

The difference is even clearer with graphics. For business charts and
line drawings, lines and edges appear smoother to all but the briefest
glance (particularly diagonal lines, which show far fewer jaggies at 600
dpi). Dithered output for continuous-tone images like photographs also
looks much improved, thanks to less visible dithering patterns.

The bottom line is simple: For everyday text printing, a 300-dpi printer
is almost certainly good enough, though higher resolution is preferable.
For desktop publishing or high-quality graphics output, you'll probably
want 600 dpi. (For a look at even higher-resolution printers, see the
sidebar "Dots Enough: Beyond 600 dpi.")

Sometimes, however, there's more to dot size than dots per inch. HP's
LaserJet III introduced a trick called Resolution Enhancement Technology,
which has since been adopted by other vendors under other names (Lexmark,
for in-stance, calls it Print Quality En-hancement Technology). This
feature concentrates on improving edges--smoothing curves and minimizing
jaggies by strategically placing smaller dots in spaces ordinarily left
between dots. Some printers also offer a similar function for gray-scale
enhancement, using sophisticated dithering patterns to increase the
perceived resolution of continuous-tone images.

Resolution enhancement provides a more obvious benefit at 300 dpi than at
600 dpi. Even at 600 dpi, though, the difference is obvious. Again, if
all you print is 10- or 12-point text, you needn't worry about it;
remember, too, that a 600-dpi printer without enhancement should easily
outdo a 300-dpi model with resolution enhancement. Still, if you want
top-quality output, it's a feature worth looking for.

The Black-and-White Choice: Inkjet or Laser?

Which technology should you choose for your black-and-white personal
printer? Laser printers have two general advantages over inkjets: higher
print quality at equivalent resolutions; and speed. There's a good deal
of overlap in speed between the best inkjets and the lowest-priced
lasers, sometimes concealed by the fact that many inkjet vendors give
speeds in characters per second (cps) rather than lasers' pages per
minute (ppm).

Some inkjet manufacturers do list performance figures in laser-like
terms--Canon, for instance, rates its BJ-200 at 4 ppm, and Lexmark claims
3 and 6 ppm for the IBM ExecJet's high-quality and draft modes,
respectively.

For all printers, remember that advertised throughput is always higher
than the real thing--claimed speeds are based on simple printing of text
using a printer's internal fonts, and don't consider the time involved in
moving paper through the printer. Nor does text speed translate into
graphics speed. Complex graphics can demand considerable processing. For
heavy-duty graphics printing, look for a printer with a built-in RISC
processor to speed the process of creating the page image.

To determine the minimum print speed you're willing to live with,
consider how many pages you have in a typical job and how long you're
willing to wait for it. If you rarely print anything longer than a
two-page letter, a 3-ppm inkjet may be fine. If you often print 40-page
reports, you may need nothing less than a 10-ppm laser.

They trail lasers in speed and quality, but inkjets are better bargains.
List prices for monochrome inkjets run from about $350 to $800, barely
overlapping the lowest-priced lasers, and street prices are well below
that. On the other hand, inkjet printers cost a bit more to use than
lasers, with their ink cartridges yielding a higher cost per page than
lasers' toner cartridges. The typical cost of a laser page is about 2
cents (with 5 percent coverage of the page area); Epson claims that its
Stylus 800 is the thriftiest of inkjets, averaging 3 cents per page. (See
the sidebar "Ecology: Printers for a Small Planet" for more about
consumables.)

Inkjets also have an edge in portability; Canon, IBM, and Hewlett-Packard
all sell inkjet printers designed specially for on-the-road use. Their
typical battery life is meager--Canon claims only 30 pages per charge for
its BJ-10ex, while HP promises 100 pages per charge for its DeskJet
Portable--but you can always plug them into a hotel-room or office wall
socket, and they're small and light enough for easy traveling. (So,
Panasonic claims, is its brand-new SideWriter KXP-5400, an AC-only
LED-based printer.)

If you decide to go the laser route, be aware that the line between
low-cost personal lasers and more traditional and expensive office laser
printers is getting fuzzy. In general, personal lasers offer speeds of 4
to 6 ppm, 300-dpi resolution, and 100- to 150-sheet input trays, for list
prices between $800 and $1,300. Business lasers, by contrast, usually
deliver 8- to 12-ppm performance, 600-dpi printing, and bigger paper
bins, with list prices starting at $1,300 and climbing to $2,000 or more.

Printers from the classic business laser category can be shared on small
networks, but depending on how prices overlap, you can just as easily
consider one for use as your desktop printer if you need a little more
speed or resolution than so-called personal lasers provide.

Pretty as a Picture

Before definitely deciding on a laser instead of an inkjet, however,
consider one more factor: inkjets' ability to put sharp black-and-white
printing and increasingly high-quality color in the same affordable
package.

Not long ago, the only route to respectable color was a color-only
printer, and the least expensive of such models--with prices in the
$3,000 to $4,000 range--were color inkjets. These could print charts on
standard copier paper, yet produced washed-out colors on transparencies,
and they couldn't print plain black-and-white text at all.

The big news in color over the past year has been the arrival of new
inkjets that offer both text printing at reasonable speeds and impressive
color at reasonable costs. The DeskJet 550C is Hewlett-Packard's most
economical example, but its color quality is less than ideal; Canon has
taken dead aim at the 550C with its new BJC-600, which combines 360-dpi
resolution and respectable 170-cps text printing with a street price
around $650.

Moving a notch higher, HP's DeskJet 1200C has a street price of about
$1,350, and offers output--on transparencies as well as copier
paper--that matches what you'd expect from a more costly thermal wax
printer. And its speed of 6 ppm for high-quality text makes it a valid
alternative to some personal lasers.

High-Class Color

Color inkjets are terrific values for presentations and simple graphics
work, but more serious desktop publishers and creative
professionals--people who don't mind buying one printer for color work
and another for correspondence--have lots of even more colorful options.
The next step above color inkjet printing, and the traditional business
choice for high-quality color, is thermal wax transfer technology.

Usually priced at $3,000 to $6,000, thermal transfer printers produce
rich, fully saturated colors on transparencies as well as on specially
coated stock. Resolution is typically 300 dpi. Thermal printers don't
handle continuous-tone images very well, showing visible dithering
patterns in scanned photos, and they don't qualify as inexpensive. Yet
their prices today are over 20 percent lower than they were a year ago.
Fargo Electronics' Primera is a thermal wax transfer printer priced at
just $995.

The next step up--and a fairly big step, with prices near $10,000 despite
similar declines over the past year--is dye-sublimation technology. (Last
summer, Kodak set a low price point for dye-sublimation printers by
pricing its ColorEase PS under $8,000.)

Dye-sublimation printers, sometimes called thermal dye transfer printers,
are known for producing photo-realistic, true-color output, with pages
that look like color photos. They work by vaporizing and merging dyes,
rather than ink or wax; the dyes diffuse into and are ab-sorbed by
specially coated paper or transparencies, yielding true continuous tones
with no dithering. As a result of the process, these printers used to be
known for blurry edges in lines and text, but the newest crop of
dye-sublimation printers has eliminated those problems.

Dye sublimation would be the unquestioned champion of color printing, if
only its high purchase price weren't equaled by its high cost per page.
Including the pricey coated paper, dye-sublimation output can cost $2.10
to $5.90 per page, compared to 50 cents to $1.50 for thermal wax transfer
and as little as 15 cents for color inkjet printing.

If the jump from thermal wax to dye sublimation is too great for you,
there's a middle step between the two technologies: solid wax printing,
which melts blocks of wax and then sprays it onto the page. With an
ink-jet, the ink dries by evaporating; with solid wax, it hardens by
cooling. The process provides output approaching the photographic quality
of dye sublimation, yet retaining the sharp edges of graphics and text,
with no need for specially coated paper. Unfortunately, once you get past
Dataproducts' $6,695 Jolt PS and Textronix's $9,995 Phaser IIIxi, solid
wax printers are hard to find.

It's difficult to accurately compare the cost per page of solid wax
printers to their rivals, since they use ink sticks or pellets. By
contrast, thermal wax and dye-sublimation printers use rolls of ribbon
sheets, with page-sized sections of colors--cyan, yellow, magenta, and
sometimes black.

Why "sometimes" black? Three-color (cyan/yellow/magenta, or CYM) printing
is faster, since the printer needs three rather than four passes to
produce an image, saving in ribbon cost. Four-color (CYMK) printing
produces a more solid black, rather than mixing a brownish or bluish
black from the other three colors. Note that color inkjets use only a
single pass no matter how many ink colors they use, so for inkjets, you
would have absolutely no reason to use anything but four-color printing.

Finally, there's the ultimate in color printing: color lasers. QMS has
just introduced the first affordable (well, almost affordable) color
laser, the $12,499 ColorScript Laser 1000, which produces excellent
300-dpi color in a single pass, while approaching 8 ppm for
black-and-white text. Still, though the QMS is only one-third to
one-quarter the price of its forebears from firms like Canon and Xerox,
it's safe to say that color laser printing is still a year or two away
from mass-market affordability. For now, if you want color and monochrome
printing in a single package, inkjets are your only real choice.

Paper, Ports, Fonts, and Memory

Once you've decided on the printer technology that best fits your needs,
you can concentrate on the features that different printers within a
category can offer. Some issues are fairly straightforward. Under the
category of paper-handling, for example, you'll want to know how much
paper the input and output trays can hold--buy a personal laser with a
skimpy 50-sheet tray, and you'll be a member of the Frequent Refillers
Club. If you need to print on B-sized (11x17-inch) paper, your printer
choices--among both inkjet and laser models--are far fewer than those
built for 8.5x11-inch paper.

Check whether you can easily feed single sheets such as letterhead,
mailing labels, and envelopes; a printer that handles envelopes
gracefully, instead of jamming at the sight of one, can be a blessing.
Several printers offer adjustable paper trays that hold envelopes; some
even include special envelope feeders.

Still, if you print a lot of enve-lopes or labels and can't afford to
grapple with a balky printer, you might want to consider a printer made
especially for addresses, such as Seiko Instruments USA's Smart Label
Printer Pro, Avery Dennison's Personal Label Printer, or CoStar's Address
Express. Such devices even come with special Windows-based address- and
label-printing software, and free you from having to change or adjust
feed trays in your primary printer.

Compatibility with your computer and software, of course, is critical. On
the hardware side, you'll want to make sure the printer offers the proper
ports--parallel, serial, AppleTalk, or network-specific--for the
connections you need. As for software, most printers come with up-to-date
drivers that let Windows and other programs take advantage of all their
features. Having to rely on more generic compatibility, such as emulation
of an older HP LaserJet or Epson dot matrix printer, is a distant second
choice.

On a related matter, you'll want to consider the printer's control
language. The standards for laser printers are PCL, the Hewlett-Packard
printer language, and Adobe's PostScript, which is popular for desktop
publishing applications (especially for users who need to create files
that will print the same way on their desktops as on a professional print
shop's or typesetter's system). A few printers skip both PCL and
PostScript in favor of GDI (Graphical Device Interface), the internal
code Windows uses to format both screen and printer output; such printers
are highly efficient with Windows, but unusable with DOS applications.

Note that PCL and PostScript come in several flavors. The older, more
limited PCL 4 is the version HP used in the LaserJet Series II; PCL 5 is
the more capable version in the LaserJet III and 4 models. As for
PostScript, the key difference between Levels 1 and 2 is the latter's
support for standard color mapping, making PostScript Level 2 the most
popular choice for high-quality color printers. Note, however, that there
are a variety of other color-matching standards, such as support for
Pantone-certified colors in printers designed for the professional
artists' market.

Fonts are as important an issue as color and compatibility--and another
reason to look for specific software drivers, since relying on, say, a
control language borrowed from a dot matrix printer may limit your choice
of fonts. Check how many fonts are built into the printer; whether
they're scalable (meaning you can scale them to any size, as with
PostScript fonts) or bit- mapped (supplied in a few fixed sizes); and
whether the printer can accept additional font cartridges or downloadable
fonts. If you use Windows and a Windows printer driver, you can always
use Windows' scalable TrueType fonts, but they may not give the fastest
performance.

Another feature you'll want to check is the amount of memory in the
printer--an important consideration for pages with large, complex images
or lots of downloaded fonts. A 300-dpi PCL laser printer, for example,
needs at least 1Mb of onboard RAM to print full-page graphics. A 600-dpi
printer needs at least 2Mb and preferably 4Mb. Very high-end printers let
you add an onboard hard drive so you can store fonts in the printer
rather than on your PC's hard disk.

And don't forget to find out about up-grades. You might not need extra
RAM or PostScript support now, but if you think you might, make sure you
can upgrade your printer rather than having to throw it out and buy
another.

Hard Copy Ahead

Forecasting printer trends is dangerous--a while back, for instance,
pundits predicted a flood of all-in-one printer/scanner/copier/FAX
products, but Okidata's Doc-It has been a lonely pioneer for many months.
Still, keep an eye out for several near-term trends. Most predictable is
a continuing drop in prices for any given speed or resolution.

The mix of monochrome and color is the best argument for buying an inkjet
printer instead of a laser. But don't count out lasers--their unbeatable
speed for high-volume printing will keep them well-established as office
workhorses, while plunging prices will ensure that personal lasers remain
a solid option for users who can get along without color. And when color
laser prices move a few thousand dollars lower, things will really get
interesting.

Come to think of it, who needs an electronic highway? Choose the right
technology for your needs, and you'll have the satisfaction of a printer
on your desk and pages in your hands for years to come.

Related Article

---------------

One Printer, Many Users

Low-cost personal printers can bring laser and near-laser quality to
everybody's desktop, but high-resolution, high-speed lasers remain the
office printers of choice for businesses needing the convenience and
money savings of shared printing. For a networked environment, printers
capable of high-volume output at 12 ppm or more, with RISC processors and
ample onboard memory to speed graphics and large print jobs, provide
quick output for all your users--even if they have to leave their desks
and walk down the hall to fetch it.

When shopping for a network printer, keep several things in mind. Look
for flexible, high-capacity paper handling, dual paper bins holding 500
sheets or more, and, ideally, duplex printing (i.e., on both sides of the
paper).

Bidirectional communication, which lets a printer inform users of its
printing status (or tell you before you send a document that the printer
is out of paper), is the next big trend. Later this year, you may find
printers bearing an NPA logo--the symbol of the Network Printing
Alliance, founded in April 1991 by Intel, Lexmark, Texas Instruments, and
Insight Development. At press time, the group was awaiting IEEE approval
of its proposed specification for a bidirectional printing protocol,
which would provide a standard set of printer-to-host commands to
exchange status, control, and configuration information.

For heavy-duty work, it's important to check the manufacturer's duty
cycle rating--how many pages the printer can produce before needing a
tuneup.

The more people sharing a printer, the higher the duty cycle you'll want.
A cycle of 50,000 pages per month or more will ensure that the printer
handles peak loads with minimal downtime.

It's more convenient to connect the printer directly to your network than
to hook it to a network server or a specific workstation. Many printers
are now available with standard or optional Ethernet or Token Ring as
well as serial, parallel, and Mac LocalTalk connections, plus automatic
emulation switching for juggling incoming PCL and PostScript jobs on the
fly.

If need be, add a print server to speed up print jobs and act as a
print-queue traffic cop. A print server attaches to the printer's
parallel port or fits into a PC's expansion slot, letting the printer
itself act as a server and eliminating the need to dedicate a PC for
print-queue management. Nonetheless, don't forget that print speed is
affected by network speed.

As with any printer purchase, your network checklist should include
enough memory to handle long print queues, plus a large assortment of
fonts. Furthermore, several office printers now combine printing with
plain-paper FAX capability. This can be a boon, unless your office
receives non-stop FAXes, which tie up the printer and leave it
un-available for its original use.

Compaq, QMS, DEC, and Hewlett-Packard have long been leaders in network
printing. As the LaserJet 4 is rapidly reclassified as a personal instead
of shared printer, HP offers the 17-ppm LaserJet 4Si MX. Compaq and DEC
offer 20-ppm Pagemarq and PrintServer models, respectively, while QMS's
3225 is a 32-ppm heavyweight.

Not only is choosing a network printer an important issue, but so is the
way you set it up. Try to find a convenient, uncluttered space, with easy
access for all. Having your documents land in printing purgatory isn't
fun, but with careful shopping, you just might avoid it.

Related Article

---------------

Ecology: Printers for a Small Planet

If the '80s motto, as spoken by Michael Douglas' character in "Wall
Street," was "Greed is good," the phrase for the '90s is "Green is good."
Last April, President Clinton dictated that government agencies must buy
computer products compliant with the Environmental Protection Agency's
Energy Star program. And you too can help conserve energy and cut your
electric bill by buying green--and, although most Energy Star products so
far have been PCs and monitors (see this month's feature on green PCs),
printers are getting into the act.

The Energy Star standard dictates that a printer's inactive power
consumption must be below 30 watts (45 watts for color printers and those
operating faster than 15 ppm). Companies like Apple, Canon, Compaq,
Dataproducts, Hewlett-Packard, Kyocera, and Lexmark--which together
account for 80 percent of printers sold in the U.S.-- have voluntarily
joined the program. Nevertheless, even a year after the first Energy Star
stickers started popping up, there's no one clear path to "green"
printing.

Both a printer's power consumption and the recyclability of its
consumable components contribute to a printer's environmental
impact--and, significantly, to its operating costs. Kyocera has focused
on waste reduction; the firm's 10- and 18-ppm Ecosys line of laser
printers use amorphous-silicon drum technology, which lets the imaging
drum last the life of the printer instead of being replaced along with
the toner cartridge. Kyocera claims the cost per page is cut down to a
penny.

Hewlett-Packard's 300-dpi, 4-ppm LaserJet 4L and the PostScript 4ML
version are the first HP LaserJets to qualify for Energy Star approval.
Laser printers rely on electricity to provide the heat that fuses toner
on paper. The 4L's "instant-on" fuser uses 5 watts in idle mode, as
opposed to the 40 watts used by the LaserJet IIP.

Similarly, Canon says its new small- or home-office laser printer, the
LBP-430, has an on-demand engine that needs virtually no warmup time,
saving 35 to 90 percent in energy costs. Canon has started a Clean Earth
Campaign for toner recycling, while Hewlett-Packard now markets
remanufactured toner cartridges.

You can also save money and help the environment without buying a new
printer. Consider recycled paper; lately the quality has risen, while the
price remains below that of new stock.

Related Article

---------------

Shopping Tips

Unless you absolutely need a printer that can handle multipart forms, dot
matrix is as dead as vaudeville. An inkjet printer is the best choice for
bargain hunters, although even the best inkjet's output is not quite as
crisp as a laser printer's.

On the other hand, inkjet technology is the best way today to get both
high-quality color and crisp black-and-white text from one printer.
Thermal wax transfer printers offer rich, sharp color for offices with
sufficient presentation or publishing volume to justify the purchase of a
separate color printer. Dye-sublimation printers offer photo-quality
color printing for Cadillac budgets.

When it comes to resolution, the difference between 300- and 600-dpi
laser printers isn't very noticeable if you print mostly text in 10- or
12-point sizes. For small or large type and for graphics, however, 600
dpi--or 300 dpi with resolution enhancement--looks sharper.

Don't take advertised printer speeds literally, but use them as relative
figures to compare different models. To convert characters per second to
pages per minute, divide by 50 (for 3,000 characters per single-spaced
page)--Epson's 110-cps Stylus 300, for example, translates to 2.2 ppm.

Graphics always take longer to print than text, so a printer with its own
RISC processor is a good choice for heavy graphics work. Graphics,
downloadable fonts, and print queues all hog memory, too, so look for at
least 2Mb for a 300-dpi laser and 4Mb for a 600-dpi unit.

The greatest software compatibility issue today is not a printer's native
language or built-in fonts, but the availability of up-to-date Windows
drivers. (Windows takes care of scalable fonts for you.)

Beyond Windows support, serious desktop publishing users--especially
those who need to transfer files across platforms or to print
shops--should look for PostScript, particularly PostScript Level 2 for
color printing. For general business printing and DOS application
support, look for compatibility with Hewlett-Packard's PCL 5.

Keep in mind the cost of consumables such as paper, and ink or toner
cartridges. Inkjets cost more per page than lasers. Some color printers
can cost close to $6 per page.

Don't forget to check paper-handling capability: how many pages a
printer's input and output trays hold, whether you need to print on
B-sized (11x17-inch) paper, and how well the printer handles envelopes
and labels.

As with any purchase, check all applicable warranties, tech support, and
return policies. If possible, visit a vendor's online forum to see what
current customers have to say.

Related Article

---------------

Dots Enough: Beyond 600 dpi

When does laser quality become typeset quality? If you thought 300-dpi
resolution looked good, but realize that 600 dpi looks better, you may be
tempted by laser printers offering even higher 800- or 1,200-dpi
resolution.

Mathematically, doubling a printer's horizontal and vertical
resolution--from 300 to 600 dpi, for example--actually increases
resolution by a factor of four (from 300x300 or 90,000 dots per square
inch to 600x600 or 360,000). Redoubling the resolution to 1,200x1,200 dpi
brings another fourfold increase in density, to 1.44 million dots per
square inch.

This is why ultra-fine printers require, in addition to print engines
capable of such resolution, lots of onboard memory: A full (completely
black) page of graphics--8.5x11 inches, with 0.25-inch margins--at 300
dpi requires 0.9Mb worth of dots. The same graphics image at 1,200 dpi
represents 14.4Mb of data.

The impression of crisper, more readable text comes from any number of
small details. With headline-sized type, for example, the sweeping curves
of a capital U appear ragged to the naked eye at 300 dpi, but much
smoother at 600 dpi. With small type sizes, characters begin to lose
separation at 300 dpi, making text harder to read.

For dithered graphics, the difference is more dramatic. Dithering, which
uses a matrix of dots to form each perceived dot or pixel of a gray-scale
image, reduces effective resolution sharply. A dithering matrix of 5x5
dots, for instance, cuts a 300x300-dpi printer down to 60x60. The same
matrix on a 600x600-dpi laser yields an effective resolution of 120x120.

Basically, the ratio between increased resolution and perceived
improvement follows a law of diminishing returns. So, while the jump from
300 to 600 dpi produces a relatively subtle difference in text quality,
the jump from an effective 60 to 120 dpi produces a much more dramatic
improvement in dithered output.

By the same token, an increase from 600 to 1,200 dpi has a small,
noticeable effect on text, while the increase in effective resolution for
dithered output, to 240 dpi, can be quite dramatic.

In this context, it's worth pointing out that typeset quality is
generally considered to be 1,200 dpi and above. If you want the best
possible output--and are willing to pay for it--you can get better than
600-dpi output today. In particular, the 600-dpi Accel-a-Writer 8100 from
Xante (1-800-926-8839) is $3,995, but you can upgrade it to 1,200 dpi for
$2,700. NewGen (1-800-756-0556) also offers a 1,200-dpi printer, the
ImagerPlus 12, for $7,495.

Eventually, 1,200--and even 2,400 dpi--will likely become standard, even
for low-end personal printers. If you're serious about desktop publishing
or extremely high-quality graphic output, you may want to consider higher
resolutions even now.

Related Article

---------------

Inkjets Dominate Desktop Color Printing

Color inkjet printers, led by entries from Canon, Eastman Kodak, Lexmark,
and especially Hewlett-Packard, dominate the market for personal color
printers. According to market-research firm Infocorp, inkjets will
continue to lead sales through 1997, though their current three-quarter
share of the market will slide to something over half. As personal color
lasers hit the market, Infocorp forecasts their popularity will grow
quickly, claiming an impressive 18 percent improvement in market share in
four years. Thermal wax transfer printers, on the other hand, show a slow
and steady market-share increase of about 2 percent per year.
