Title:     The road to 1994 is paved with good intentions.
             (New Year's resolutions for others in the computer industry
             to keep)
Author:    Schwartz, Gil


Abstract:  Various parties in the computer industry should make New
           Year's resolutions for 1994 that would improve the industry.
           Hardware manufacturers should not hire such a low proportion
           of support staff to sales staff so that customers can receive
           excellent service not only before they buy but after as well.
           Peripherals should not come with cards configured to default
           at Interrupt five or seven, since most sound cards and LPT
           devices are assigned to these interrupts. Software
           manufacturers should limit their programs to a reasonable size
           and should call patches, fixes and kludges product recalls
           rather than upgrades, releasing them with an apology. CD-ROM
           software should especially bring something new to users.
           Peripheral manufacturers should make all their products comply
           with the small computer system interface (SCSI) standard.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Before we can say "posttraumatic holiday disorder," 1994 will be upon us,
full of new challenges, new hardware and software, new hypes, new gripes,
new ways to spend wisely or waste foolishly that most precious of
commodities: time. Another year dead. Another year ahead. There's only
one way to deal with it. No, we're not talking about eating, drinking,
and playing Spear of Destiny until we keel over onto the industrial
carpet. That's a year-round thing. Today we're talking about indulging in
the formulation of good, solid resolutions that shape our hopes and
dreams for the year to come.

So let's . . . resolve!

Except for one thing. I have very little interest in making and keeping
the same old stupid resolutions--do you? I thought not. How much better
would it be to suggest some great intentions that others can keep.

Be it resolved that hardware manufacturers shall not get away with hiring
one tuna-stained tech support guy for every 1,800 sharkskin salespeople,
requiring poor, unsuspecting customers (who up until they plunked down
their moolah received exemplary service) to sit on hold until moss grows
beneath their buttocks when their motherboards fail after two days of
infrequent use. Or their modems utilize a proprietary command set. Or
their B: drives won't read low-density disks. Use of the message, "All
our tech support people are currently on the line. Please hold and your
call will be answered in the order in which it was received," followed by
30 minutes of insipid new age music and obnoxious, jolly sales pitches
will be punishable by ten days of listening to Vice President Al Gore
talk about the information superhighway.

And while we're at it, be it resolved that no peripherals shall come with
cards configured to default at Interrupt 5 or 7. How stupid can you be?
Don't you know that just about every sound card and LPT device is
assigned to one of those locations? And speaking of which, you know those
tiny little jumpers that leap off your thumb when you're trying to move
them around the board and lodge themselves behind the 3,000-pound
credenza, effectively disabling the entire mechanism before you even
installed it? Lose 'em!

Be it resolved also that the folks who bring us our tasty software make
at least a tentative effort to limit the size of their programs to
something reasonable. I mean, come on! At this point your basic program,
no matter how negligible its purpose, must contain at least four
high-density 3 1/2-inch floppies compressed to hold as much information
as Exit 3 off the Internet. The installation process takes as long as the
construction of a small barn. Even when the Moby Dick-sized monster comes
on CD-ROM, the eventual spread it occupies on your overwrought hard drive
puts a Sumo wrestler to shame. All to note down where you're supposed to
have lunch with Mr. Finster, or to catalog all employees with bad teeth
for a study of future dental costs.

And be it in addition resolved that any patch, fix, or kludge that must
be issued within eight weeks of a major software release not be referred
to as an "upgrade" at all, but as a "product recall," with mandated
"We're very sorry for your trip to the mental institution that resulted
when your entire video function was disabled by the way our kernel uses
high memory" announcements to be made in all major computer magazines,
including of course this one (even though I think you'll agree it's
gratifyingly fat already).

And oh yeah, be it really resolved that all CD-ROMs bring something
interesting to the table, and not merely be inert repositories of boring
writing, minuscule pictures, and video clips of alarming brevity. The
function of these things is to haul information retrieval into a newer,
bolder, more immediate form-- not simply replicate the dry, juiceless
exercises that made our school days an ongoing fight against narcolepsy.
Those who fail to meet this resolution shall be forced to scan 24-bit
tiff files of insects until they weep.

Be it further resolved that manufacturers of scanners, hard drives, tape
drives, CD-ROMs, and other peripherals will be taken out behind the
boathouse and flogged if their machines do not easily comply with the
SCSI standard, making them impossible to daisy-chain and requiring a
proprietary board that hogs a whole slot and doesn't work with the
fabulous software drivers from Corel and others. I'm talking about you,
Nikon! Get with the program!

Finally, let's make the appropriate parties resolve to cut down on
blue-sky, dreamscape cyberchat that paints a future bearing no
resemblance to anything that normal people can understand. Possibly let's
resolve to take a break from the entire concept of virtual anything
unless we want folks to think we're nothing more than consultants
attempting to generate a living by making other people feel more stupid
than we actually are. Are you listening, Mitch Kapor?

Of course, as is only fair, I have a few reasonable resolutions of my
own.

I resolve to be Pentium-ready, even when I feel like dozing off after a
hard day at the office.

I resolve to be equally open to the promise of OS/2 and Windows NT for as
long as it's absolutely necessary.

I resolve to have a vision, even if Lou Gerstner says I don't need one.

'Nuff said.
