             related article on TCP's connection-oriented features) (PC
             Week LABS: Tech View) (PCWEEK Netweek)
Author:    Chernicoff, David P.


Abstract:  The Transmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol's (TCP/IP)
           overall design and functioning merit description, now that
           many industry observers see it becoming the national data
           superhighway's principal transport system. TCP/IP is not a
           single thing, but rather a suite of protocols. The Internet
           Protocol (IP), which carries data between two systems without
           first requiring their connection, is fundamental. IP does not
           guarantee the data will reach its destination, however, though
           it tries its best to do so. Neither can it break large packets
           down into smaller ones for transmission, or recover lost or
           damaged packets. IP does support routing and error control.
           Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) runs atop IP to provide
           connection-oriented services. It ensures that data reaches its
           destination, no matter how many hops and how much division
           into smaller packets are required. TCP also uses flow control
           to prevent data overloads at the receiving end. The common
           Internet services FTP and Telnet run on top of TCP.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Now that we're all being asked to meander down the national data
superhighway, it's time we became familiar with the services it will
offer travelers, as well as where it can take us.

Trade and business publications talk about TCP/IP as the transport on
this highway, giving short shrift to the fact that TCP/IP is a suite of
protocols rather than a single entity. The Transmission Control Protocol
(TCP) sits on top of the Internet Protocol (IP) and provides
connection-oriented features not available simply through IP.

IP is a connectionless protocol that allows data to be passed between two
systems without a prior connection. However, IP does not provide
guaranteed delivery of the datagram (also called Protocol Data Unit, or
PDU); rather, it offers only a "best-effort" attempt at data delivery. If
the datagram is lost or damaged, IP contains no mechanism for recovery.

IP does support fragmented PDUs. This support allows the IP to break
datagrams into a size that is appropriate for the type of network
connection being used. Such an ability is very useful in the WAN
environment -- without it, WAN gateways would have to handle all packet
fragmentation.

Along with the packet-fragmentation service, IP also provides a number of
other services, such as the Internet header-check routine, which checks a
datagram for a valid IP header, that help render the network invisible to
the user. If everything passes these checks, the destination address is
checked and the packet is transmitted. If the datagram fails any validity
check, it is discarded.

Datagram routing

The IP gateway also makes routing decisions based on the routing list. It
is capable of routing within the local network or to other networks.
Routing is generally done based on a distance metric, which is often the
lowest number of hops between networks. IP can also use source routing.
Source routing allows a protocol at a higher layer to determine how IP
routes the datagram. IP is also capable of recording the route traveled
and time-stamping the datagram.

The ICMP, or Internet Control Message Protocol, provides IP's error
control. ICMP reports errors in PDU processing and also provides some
administrative and status messaging. ICMP can report when no host is
found or if the lifetime of the PDU expires.

Because most systems use a connection-oriented protocol, TCP is used to
provide these connection-oriented services. TCP is designed to run over
IP, providing the guaranteed deliverability needed in many environments.
In other words, TCP is responsible for the transmission of data from
originator to receiver, be it across one or multiple networks.

The services commonly thought of as part of the Internet, such as FTP,
Telnet, and SMTP, all sit on top of TCP. That is, they use TCP as the
transport protocol to implement their services. TCP, in turn, uses IP to
transfer data, while retaining responsibility for managing the network
connection.

TCP gets information from the levels above it as a data stream, one byte
at a time, which it groups into TCP segments. These segments are then
passed to the IP layer.

On the receiver side, TCP also handles flow control, to prevent buffer
overrun (which could result in lost data), or saturation of the receiving
system. This is done using a windowing mechanism that provides a value to
the transmitter; this value informs the transmitter how many bytes can be
transmitted before it must pause.

TCP/IP became much more widespread in the business community when the
practice of loading multiple-protocol stacks started to become
commonplace. For example, in PC Week Labs, we run an IPX/SPX stack to
connect to our Novell Inc. NetWare network, a NetBIOS stack to access
Lotus Development Corp. Notes servers, and a TCP/IP stack to connect to
an Oracle Corp. database that resides on a Digital Equipment Corp. VAX.

Because we use a Windows-based IP implementation, our multiple-protocol
stack can be loaded and unloaded dynamically; this affords us the luxury
of not using a large amount of memory unless the IP stack is needed.

Running TCP/IP allows PC Week Labs analysts to access newsgroups on the
Internet, as well as glean information from anonymous FTP sites
throughout the world. The Labs can also set up systems as FTP sites and
function as peer servers to other users within our organization.
