Title:     Acrobatic kids.
             (Adobe's 'Kids Take the Digital Road' software grant program
             donates Adobe Acrobat software) (Brief Article)
Author:    Levin, Carol


-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Look at any social studies or geography textbook in any classrom in
America today, and chances are it's hopelessly out of date. That's
because updating texts to keep pace with world events is too expensive.
Now, software companies and publishers are hoping that technology can
solve the problem.

Adobe's new "Kids Take the Digital Road" software grant program is a $5
million donation of Adobe Acrobat software to public schools
(800-521-1976). Its goal is to get more electronic information into
classrooms and to establish Acrobat's .PDF (portable document format) as
the standard format for electronic documents.

Acrobat is just one of the many programs that publishers are using to
digitize books and documents. There's also Farallon's Replica, No Hands
Software's Common Ground, Voyager's Expanded Book, and the SGML standard.
Acrobat preserves a document's look and feel across platforms (see PC
Magazine, November 9, 1993).

Electronic document software means texts can be produced, distributed,
and updated at a fraction of the cost of paper format. Acrobat will let
students create their own electronic "portable" newsletters and reports
for on-line distribution.

Kids' publications such as Sports Illustrated for Kids and The Wall
Street Journal, Classroom Edition, are now experimenting with the idea.
And the California Technology Project's Guide software, a graphical
Internet front end, has incorporated Acrobat to open up a vast array of
original materials from the Library of Congress archives.

But roadblocks remain, such as wiring classrooms for phone lines and
getting more PCs into schools so kids aren't left in the dust of the
electronic superhighway.
