Title:     Step up and claim your role in building the new highway.
             (information superhighway)
Author:    Hill, Thomas


Abstract:  Corporations and governments as well as public and private
           enterprises should have the opportunity to help shape the
           information highway. The design of this future interstate
           commerce platform for providing goods and services naturally
           ought to reflect the ideas of those buying the goods and
           services. These consumers can ask their suppliers to provide
           data through electronic data interchange (EDI), and they can
           install Internet and other public data network connections.
           They ought to offer gateways to public electronic-mail
           (E-mail) networks as well. E-mail addresses should be
           published. These users should also take advantage of the
           services offered by telephone and cable companies, which can
           provide low-cost connectivity to public networks.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Recently, one of my fellow Corporate Partners discussed what the
information highway was going to look like. I would like to enlist your
help in building it. The information highway is the future interstate
commerce platform for providing goods and services to corporate,
government, private, and public enterprises. Everyone has a role to play
to bring the highway into being.

As a buyer of goods and services, you can request your suppliers to
provide your company with data via EDI (electronic data interchange).
Have your company install connections to the Internet and other public
data networks. Provide gateways to public E-mail networks, and publish
your sales force's E-mail addresses. Have your sales personnel collect
E-mail addresses from their customers, and have them make those addresses
available to management.

On the home front, check into the services that your telephone and cable
companies are offering. Give them a call and let them know that you are
interested in low-cost connectivity to public networks. Ask them about
their plans for introducing high-speed connections into the home via
cable or ISDN services.

If you are considering building a new house, tell your builder that you
want category 5 cabling installed. After he responds with "huh?", hand
him a Black Box catalog and show him what it is. The additional cost is
minimal, and the wiring will support the computers and cable equipment
that are coming down the road.

Government information is quickly becoming available on BBSs and the
Internet. It ranges from federal agency bulletin boards to the Securities
and Exchange Commission filings on the Internet. Try out the NTIA
(National Telecommunications and Information Administration) at (202)
482-1199.

Our schools and libraries are building connections to allow people to
browse the shelves and request books to be placed on hold. Soon these
publications will be available on a computer screen near you. The
publishing community is currently testifying to Congress about the use of
electronic media on the information highway.

As a parent, introduce your kids to your computers and modems. Let them
try out a bulletin-board service or two to get the feel of it, and let
them show you what they find. Become involved in the PTA and push for
their schools to get connections to the Internet. We may putt along the
information highway, but our kids will soon be cruising it like Main
Street.

I've outlined a number of possible roles for you in building the
information highway. Select the one that appeals to you and pursue it
with a passion. Hope to see you in the fast lane.
