Title:     Test run on the info superhighway.
             (Trends) (Brief Article)
Author:    Perenson, Melissa J.


-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Long before the information superhighway winds its way through every home
in America, a group of scientists and researchers are gearing up for a
test run to demonstrate distributed computing over a high-speed network.
In the process, the companies building the National Information
Infrastructure Testbed (NIIT) hope to turn theory into commercial reality
and work through the logistical quagmires that are bound to surface.

Slated to go on-line in November 1993, the Earth Data System testbed is
the first in a series of NIIT experiments. It brings together scientists
and policymakers from across the country who are involved in ecological
issues. The next one, scheduled for 1994, will tackle health care
administration.

Earth Data Systems connects nine sites across in the U.S. into a
high-speed network serving 800 gigabytes of video, audio, data, and text.
Ethernet or FDDI workstations use TCP/IP protocol to communicate with
other sites across the long-distance network's frame relay or
asynchronous transfer mode (ATM) switches. The high-bandwidth network
runs at 45 megabits per second for fiber optic ATM and 1.5 Mbps for
frame-relay running over T1 circuits.

The network is the brainchild of a consortium, including AT&T, Department
of Energy, Digital Equipment Corp., Ellery Systems, Hewlett-Packard,
Sandia National Labs, Smithosonian Astrophysical Observatory, and Sprint.
"The purpose of NIIT is to work out a variety of issues around providing
a national information structure, ranging from the technology of
interconnection to the business issues of providing the service and the
legislative issues regulating this service," says Robert Bismuth of
Digital.

The benefits of EDS will be tremendous. Users of the multimedia workgroup
application can access information seamlessly, regardless of where that
information is geographically located. Access is limited to Unix
workstations, though universal access via the Internet is planned.
Meanwhile, the NIIT's findings from this dry run will be shared with
lawmakers now pondering policies for the future information highway.
