Title:     Inside track.
Author:    Dvorak, John C.


-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

There's a lot of talk in the industry about IBM's new "clean room"
project to create its own version of the 486 microcode. The purported
goal is to add silicon to the PowerPC 601 chip to allow IBM's
next-generation PC the ability to run both native x86 apps and PowerPC
apps.

I've always found this project a bit peculiar, since the 601 is supposed
to be the perfect chip for emulation, and you'd think that would be a
cheaper way to go. Well, some people now believe that IBM is fashioning a
big misinformation campaign--that the company is indeed
reverse-engineering the 486, but that this project has nothing to do with
the PowerPC. Instead, IBM intends to clone the 486 and the Pentium as
well so it can produce and sell chips against Intel (and AMD, and Cyrix,
and TI). This is where the money is.

Currently, IBM has a license to make Intel chips but is restricted from
selling them, except for use in its own systems or on IBM motherboards.
It can't sell raw chips under the license. While IBM has suddenly become
a leader in motherboard manufacturing with a line of motherboards
containing IBM's 486, it wants to sell bulk processors--especially the
clock-tripled chips that Intel seems reluctant to produce. Some observers
watching the current aggressiveness of IBM are calling it the "wounded
bear syndrome." That is, IBM sees everyone as the enemy and intends to be
in all markets.

Meanwhile, Intel is still struggling internally with the Pentium. The
company needs to get the Pentium into the market, but it's essentially
losing money on each chip it makes. Intel's not making as much money as
it would make if the time and resources were instead spent on 486
production. The word in the valley is that the company loses seven 486s
when it makes one Pentium. This is a function of yield and die-size.
Since the 486DX2/66 sells for about $400 and the Pentium sells for about
$950, you can see why certain Intel managers--whose compensations are
adjusted as profits go up and down--are squawking.

Dvorak's Quick Analysis: In fact, Intel is doing the right thing by
forcing the Pentium out of the door. Intel is a technology leader, and
its leadership is paramount to continued success. It has to push the
newest stuff at the expense of a cash cow. No bull!

Trends You Can Count On: As you know, I've been following the upcoming
bloodbath in hi-res monitors. Every monitor company is jockeying for the
dominant slot by offering new features. Just as multisync, multiscan
monitors dominated the late 1980s, look for something called Continuous
Scan to dominate the rest of this decade. Sony will probably be first
with one as it tries to wrestle the number-one spot away from NEC, which
has been coasting with its FG series for a couple of years.

Internet Humor Dept.: Anyone with an Internet connection knows it's good
for three things: (1) cheap e-mail, (2) rapid propagation of bogus
rumors, (3) nerdy urban folklore (a.k.a. jokes and humorous observations
passed from person to person). Here's the latest story passed around the
net:

True story, happened yesterday. Paul Mockapetrus was at Bellcore watching
a demonstration of Tennenhouse's Vu-net connected to a Sunshine switch
and the Aurora network. The Vu-net physical hardware is roughly three
large PC boards sitting on a table with wires hanging all over the place.
The Sunshine switch was sitting next to it, with even more wires hanging
out.

Paul M (standing over Vu-net and peering at it): "Sure doesn't look like
an information superhighway to me."

Bruce Davie: "Do you want me to paint a yellow stripe down the middle?"

I guess you had to be there.

The MCI Mail Test Dept.: Although customer service denied that MCI has a
14.4-kilobit-per-second link, the company's been testing it for a few
months. Set your modem to 38,400 bits per second and call the old MCI
2,400-bps modem line at 800-456-6245 and bingo! You're connected at
V.32bis (14.4 kilobits per second) and V.42bis. Great speed for those
Zmodem downloads. I suppose MCI isn't talking about it since it seems to
run only about 20 percent faster than the 9,600-bps link. If you're into
speed, then also check CompuServe for the new 14.4-Kbps phone numbers.
Gee, just in time for V.FAST.

Genuinely Interesting Gizmo Dept.: It's called the MotorMouse, a
switchable two- or three-button mouse in the shape of a Lamborghini or
Corvette. You push down on the hood to get the button action. The mouse
comes in red, white, and yellow. The red Corvette looks great! List price
is $65.99, but there's an introductory offer at $59.95. This is a perfect
gift for the person who has everything. The company can be reached by
calling 604-681-6062, or writing MotorMouse at 126 Garden Ave., North
Vancouver, BC V7P 3H2 or P.O. Box 9754, 3873 Airport Way, Bellingham, WA
98227-9754.
