Title:     The NII materializes.
             (National Information Infrastructure)


Abstract:  The Earth Data System (EDS), announced in Nov 1993, represents
           the first application of the National Information
           Infrastructure Testbed (NIIT), a high-performance network that
           will interconnect nine sites across the nation using
           asynchronous transfer mode (ATM), frame relay and fiber
           distributed data interface (FDDI). The EDS will involve a
           suite of environmental research and analysis applications.
           Researchers in various locations will share environmental data
           and image files across an ATM-based network. Oregon State
           University, University of New Hampshire and University of
           California at Santa Barbara (UCSB) are working on the first
           EDS application, a deforestation monitoring program.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

THE SUPERHIGHWAY ON A BEATEN TRACK

Until now, the electronic superhighway has existed only in the ether. But
with the November debut of the Earth Data System (EDS), the National
Information Infrastructure became a beaten track.

The EDS is the first application of the National Information
Infrastructure Testbed (NIIT), a high-speed network that will link nine
sites across the United States using ATM, frame relay, and FDDI.
Representatives from U.S. industry, academia, and government lead the
NIIT consortium.

"We will run lab-tested applications in a real-world environment to see
if we meet the customer needs," says Dr. John Gibbons, assistant to the
president for Science and Technology and director of the Office of
Science and Technology policy based in Washington, D.C.

The EDS is a suite of environmental research and analysis applications.
Researchers in different locations will use these distributed
applications to share the environmental data and image files across an
ATM network. Oregon State University, University of New Hampshire, and
University of California at Santa Barbara (UCSB) are working on the first
application in the EDS suite: a deforestation monitoring program.
Researchers at these sites and around the country will use the NIIT to
share gigabytes of landsat and other satellite imagery and data to
analyze the level of deforestation in a particular area, for example.

"One of the problems is how the scientists get at that information. How
do they store it? Each image can be hundreds of megabytes to a gigabyte.
Once the scientists have the information, they have different models and
analyses they want to run it through. Then how do they collaborate with
other researchers in the United States and throughout the world?" asks
Jeff Jordan, vice president at Ellery Systems (Boulder, CO). Ellery Open
Systems software provides the Distributed Computing Environment (DCE)
component of the deforestation application.

The primary NIIT sites--University of New Hampshire, Oregon State, Sandia
National Laboratories, and Hewlett-Packard--will interconnect through
Sprint's ATM network at the DS-3 speed of 45Mbps. The secondary
sites--UCSB and University of California at Berkeley--will access the EDS
through frame relay services. Unlike the lower-speed Internet, the NIIT
provides a venue to test distributed applications on a high-speed, ATM
road.

NIIT members argue that the NII is essential to the U.S. economy. "The
quality of information determines how well businesses can compete in a
global market," says Lew Platt, president and CEO of Hewlett-Packard. "We
must stimulate the development of key technologies. You can develop them
in the isolation of a research lab, or you can do it in the NIIT where
you can create a market pull."

Members of the NIIT include AT&T, Ellery Systems, Essential
Communications, Hewlett-Packard, Network Systems, Oregon State
University, Sandia National Labs, Smithsonian Atrophysical Observatory,
Sprint, SynOptics, and University of New Hampshire. A healthcare
application is planned for 1994.
